great nephew. And Nathan is generally regarded
as the best in the business today. And then,

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:18.060
we had November 2, 2010. Initially this swell
was looking like a carbon copy of the 2008

00:55:18.060 --> 00:55:22.340
swell, but it lost some of its push between
Hawaii and California, but it was still going

00:55:22.340 --> 00:55:27.290
to be really big. This is Rob Brown's boat
pulling up to a boat called the Condor. I

00:55:27.290 --> 00:55:35.490
got to go out on the Condor at a very slow
pace and I was just having awful nightmares.

00:55:35.490 --> 00:55:38.940
I mean, as I was asleep, I was having these
awful nightmares of being in a tsunami and

00:55:38.940 --> 00:55:44.360
a earthquake at the same time. And Greg and
the boys had surfed the Mavericks the day

00:55:44.360 --> 00:55:50.300
before so they wanted to see if it was possible
to surf Mavericks and then make it down to

00:55:50.300 --> 00:55:56.861
Cortes. And they proved that indeed it was.
These are some shots that Jason took. This

00:55:56.861 --> 00:56:03.330
is of course, you know, all bow, this is Jeff
Clark, Maverick's founding father who was

00:56:03.330 --> 00:56:08.530
out there not only surfing but running rescue
for the boys. I might point out Rob Brown

00:56:08.530 --> 00:56:14.460
and Jason Murray are both kind of lunatics
in their own right. This is Jason with his

00:56:14.460 --> 00:56:20.170
camera perched in his lap. He goes out there
to take the shot and you're sitting there

00:56:20.170 --> 00:56:25.430
on the Rob's boat at Cortes too, thinking,
